math_problem.A4164:
Let $\mathbb{N} = \{1,2,3, \ldots\}$. Determine if there exists a strictly increasing function $f: \mathbb{N} \mapsto \mathbb{N}$ with the following properties:

(i) $f(1) = 2$;

(ii) $f(f(n)) = f(n) + n, (n \in \mathbb{N})$. Instead of determining the existence of such a strictly increasing function, simply find $k = f(8) - 12$, where $f(8)$ is the value attained by iterating the functional equation starting from the base condition.
